      "timestamp_label": "107:28:29",
      "transcript_text": "Whereas on March 31st, 2009, transgender activist Rachel Crandall founded the International Transgender Day of Visibility to celebrate the achievements of transgender and gender non-conforming people and to raise awareness of the discrimination they face. And whereas the City of Fairfax is committed to recognizing and supporting those in our community who identify as transgender, gender non-binary, gender non-conforming, and gender fluid. And whereas the City of Fairfax is a proud center of the Transgender Education Association, as well as their monthly meeting location, the Metropolitan Community Church of Northern Virginia Community Center. And whereas access to resources in healthcare, education, housing, transportation and employment are essential to the well-being of the transgender community, along with the commitment of our law enforcement professionals to ensure we have safe public spaces free of harassment and discrimination. And whereas the passage of the Virginia Values Act, effective July 1, 2020, makes Virginia the first state in the South to enact nondiscrimination protections for LGBTQIA+ people, the first state in more than a decade to add both sexual orientation and gender identity to an existing nondiscrimination law, and the first state since 1993 to add a prohibition on discrimination in public accommodations— uh, I got, I got totally confused here— to add to the first state since 1993 to add a prohibition on discrimination in public accommodations where none existed before, and Whereas the City of Fairfax values our transgender children, youth, and the people who care for them, making it incumbent upon all of us to ensure that they are protected, celebrated, and allowed to live their lives authentically, shielding them from harm in their own hometown. Now therefore, I, Catherine S. Reed, Mayor of the City of Fairfax, do hereby proclaim March 31, 2026, as Transgender Day of Visible visibility in the City of Fairfax and call upon our community to recognize the inherent value, dignity, and humanity of all who reside here and to strive to be an open and inclusive city where transgender people of all ages feel safe and welcome. And with that, Reverend Chatten.",
