      "timestamp_label": "341:51:34",
      "transcript_text": "Good evening, Mayor Reed, City Council, Mike Fabio, Chainbridge Road. What would you say if someone came up to you and said they would give you a valuable piece of property in affluent Fairfax County for free, and he further said that he would pay for over half the cost of placing a building on that and claimed he had figured out a way that the cost of construction stayed on target once the project was started. But one condition would be that in that building, he reserves the right to continue to provide you with public healthcare, women, infant, and child services, dentistry, immunization, and vital records. You would naturally be skeptical. What's the catch? What would you have to pay? Something valuable in return? Perhaps trade another property? He says, no, you keep your property. Do whatever you wish with it. No strings attached. However, there's one catch. After 99 years, I'm going to take the property back unless you pay me a dollar. That's the situation we have right now with the Willard Sherwood project. Yet there are real concerns that City Council will turn this deal down. It's wasted money to continue to repair Green Acres with no plan in sight. When the time comes that the new building is the only choice, how long will it take for you to plan get public support for that project? Another 10 years? And what will it cost? Certainly much more than it's on the table right now. Don't look this gift horse in the mouth. Vote yes for the Willard Sherwood Project.",
