      "transcript_text": "Well, like I think Davenport said, we need to look at it every year. I mean, I know with, with, even though ours is a smaller amount, in 2014 when the water system was sold, the sanitary sewer system was turned over to Public Works. And speaking with the, the finance director back then, they really hadn't been focusing on a lot of the capital projects a lot of the money wasn't being spent. So, uh, Mr. Ito and the Street Superintendent and I were very aggressive in an analysis program, and we've spent a lot of money lining pipes. And I think in some regards— and Mr. Remsen and Annie could, could give more detail— we've caught up in some of the pipelining. And when you line a pipe, it could last 30 to 50 years, and that was one of the reasons why when we took over, some of the increases were more than 6%. And, but I think that we have caught up. And Satoshi, if you'd like to talk about the condition now as it was when we took over.",
