      "transcript_text": "We would not take all that in year one. We would phase that out as it is needed while we're doing that construction. It's also the most prudent approach to do. Uh, one, you don't want to just have idle money sitting there while it's not being fully utilized. And then two, the amount of potential burden on the residents or the average homeowner when it comes to the tax bill. The other potential factor is, as discussed during our budget retreat, we are anticipating inflation or interest rate to actually come down from where it currently is at 4% to about 3%. So that would be something that would also be beneficial when we actually issue the debt. In terms of some considerations in terms delay or canceling the project. Delay impacts— currently we're, we're done with the design, we're 100% done with the design, we're near complete with the permitting, we're ready, assuming project approval. If we get project approval, construction would start this summer. Any delays based on $127 million at escalation, each month is about $400,000 every month we lose. If we lose too much time, the bids expire. The bids are actually good for 60 days. We've built in a kind of a retainer to keep those bids live for a little bit longer because of the date that we anticipate that would be ready for award in late April or May. But if we exceed past that, then the project would need to be rebid, potentially rebid. Moving or cancellation. So the city The city has $4 million currently that's been expended, actually a little closer to $4.5 million now. The county impacts are restarting the design. The county has $8 million of sunk costs that they've paid to date, roughly. And then it's estimated that the redesign and associated escalation and extending the Health Department lease would be another $12 million. So total impact to the county about $20 million. The other thing in terms of the Green Acres, I kind of look at it as Green Acres have been running on bald tires for a while. So you run a big risk of a major repair landing in your lap or losing the service that are provided at that facility.",
