      "timestamp_label": "1037:09:36",
      "transcript_text": "So in the comprehensive plan, we do have a very specific goal to develop and implement a climate and energy action plan. And we have specific targets of greenhouse gas reductions. And with that, we'll kind of get into what we— what I think we really accomplished that I wanted to highlight. Within climate action. So we have— the green building policy was developed and completed, and I thought that that was a huge, a huge win for the city. And I was quite involved in that because I was reviewing it as an— as a— just as a citizen. It was one of my interests. So kudos to the staff, kudos to the council for actually getting it completed. And now we have to get it adopted and actually put it into practice. The second set of projects that I'm going to highlight are the ones that are kind of lighting related. And the reason why I'm kind of wanted to highlight this is because these projects show the economic potential of projects like this. So for example, when you look at the LED streetlight conversion project, I mean, you do a very quick back-of-the-envelope calculation and you could probably end up with a savings of about $150K a year. So that might be significant enough to offset any staffing costs. And I know we all have budgetary challenges, so this is the kind of thinking that could help address your budgetary challenges. So that was the key point I wanted to make, was that we need to start looking at things with an ROI lens and not just treat projects as sunk costs. So that's a good example of that. Moving on to what I think opportunities for improvement. So the one that— I feel very strongly about is, you know, we obviously— the comprehensive plan calls for, for the, the climate action plan. It was first funded in 2024, kept getting deferred, and probably will not get started this year as well. So that would be 3 years in a row. The earliest I'm told it'll get started is in 2028. So as you can see, that, you know, a very critical component of our comprehensive plan is not really going to be even started for a while. And so our recommendation is that we reprioritize this. I think we need to put the horse before the cart and actually develop the plan before we start implementing all the climate action projects. So, we really need a course correction there. So, that is, I think, our first action. The second one I notice is we need to start making a transition to being more metrics-driven. And start— and that requires actually putting in instrumentation. So, you know, rather than just simply tracking action, we actually start tracking traction, which requires metrics. So an example would be if one of our goals is to complete 100% renewables in the city operations by 2035, which is hardly, you know, 9 years away from now, and you're trying to hit approximately 10% a year, we have nothing to tell us whether we are actually achieving that or not. So that's the reason why I think we need to start putting in the instrumentation. And I think the first baby step we need to do is— and that's our recommendation— is to start with the utility data management software. It's not— it's a modest cost. I think it's been on the books for a while. I'm just not clear on why it's not getting implemented. But that will help you track your energy usage. So once you've got a handle on the energy usage, then you can actually create programs to improve it and measure the improvement. Um, next slide please. Oh, I wanted to point out, in case you're curious about where the other localities stand, uh, vis-à-vis the Climate Action Plan, I've actually compiled all our neighboring, uh, local governments, and you can see every single one of them has completed their Climate Action Plan, including the City of Falls Church, which is smaller than us. So clearly they're assigning a very high priority, and, and I think we would be wise to, to start working on this and getting this done and then executing all our climate projects. Next slide, please. So these are the climate action recommendations. I'm going to skip on 3 of these because I'm going to also cover the overall recommendations from the ESC, but I will highlight one, which is one of the recommendations is for this— I'm told that the City Council has not adopted their strategic goals and priorities for 26-27. I know this is precedence, and the problem is that it creates a lot of confusion when it comes to project prioritization. And so I would strongly urge so that we get the specific direction that we are looking for. We have to break the comprehensive and the strategic plan, which are looking out— the comprehensive plan is looking out 15 to 25 years. The strategic plan is looking out maybe 3 to 5 years. But what are we going to do for the next 2 years, that's the term that you all are here for, and so that we can be very focused on the execution side and trying to align with that. So my recommendation is please adopt your strategic goals and priorities, and if possible, make them SMART. Make them very specific, measurable, achievable, relevant, time-bound, so that they really are actionable. So that would be our request. With that, we'll move on to— I'm also going to cover the overall recommendations from the ESC. Next slide, please. So if there is one slide, if there's one takeaway from this entire presentation, it would be this one, because this summarizes the top 7 recommendations from everything that everyone's talked about. So this is kind of our unanimous position on what we think are the key takeaways from this presentation. So the first one right at the top is— you've heard this multiple times— is you need to— we need to really staff the climate and energy manager position. And you will see later on that there's several other projects that are actually dependent on this. So if we don't get this done, we will not be able to do the others. So number one is staffing the climate and energy management manager position. We just talked about this. Help us focus, adopt the strategic goals and priorities, sit down and think about what it is that you'd like the ESE and in, in environment and sustainability, what are the specific things that you'd like us to accomplish from the overarching strategic and comprehensive plan. Next. Adopt and operationalize the Green Building Policy. We've already developed it, but it needs to be adopted, it needs to be put in practice, and the only way to get that done is if you have that staffing position, because it does require 25 hours a week of staffing resource. So that, that is another one of our recommendations. Next. And then you've heard about this. I think we need to course correct on the Climate Action Plan. We need to reprioritize that. We need to fast-track it. And we need to make sure we pull it in from fiscal year '28. To as early as possible, because I think the risk, especially on the adaptation side, is huge. And we have done absolutely no work on adaptation. We've started some work on mitigation, but that's a whole new assessment of risk to the city and what response— our response is going to be. Again, this one requires the climate and energy manager position. So one FTE could actually probably fill in both of those roles and be able to get all 3 projects off the ground. Next. One more.",
