      "turn_index": 18,
      "start_seconds": 328424,
      "timestamp_label": "91:13:44",
      "transcript_text": "Motion passed unanimously. We will move on to public hearing. Our first public hearing is on the Fern Street Connector Path Project, and there's no council action on this item tonight. I'm going to recognize Chloe Ritter, the multimodal transportation planner, to provide the staff presentation. Okay, good evening, Mayor and Council. We are here, this item, uh, to discuss the Fern Street connector path and have a public hearing on this. But before we get started, let's see, I would like to just briefly introduce Our consultant, Megan Waring, who is from Kimley-Horn, so she will be here helping me discuss the design of the project. And then we also have some other staff in the audience in case there are questions that we need to answer. So the purpose of the public hearing is to give some background on the project and give a design presentation. After we give the presentation, we will answer questions and invite public comment. But this is a design public hearing where no public— no City Council action is required. So we are really here just to listen and take feedback and then there will be a public comment period that goes on for another week and then we will give responses to all of the comments at the end of that period. So first, the project overview. The location of this project is the— on Fern Street just south of Route 29. This came out of the Camp Washington Small Area Plan and it is a connection between the Fern Street dead end that is just south of Route 29 and the intersection of Fern Street and Park Road just south of that. And right now that is kind of a grassy area and this project would build a pedestrian and bicycle connection to connect the commercial area with the neighborhood and activate that green space and that open space in the Camp Washington Activity Center. This is where we are on the project. We are here at Step 10. As I said, this is a Design Public Hearing for the intermediate design plans this evening. And this is where we have been on the project so far. As I said, this came out of the Camp Washington Small Area Plan which was adopted in 2022. And then the project was advanced in the 2-year transportation program. We had an open house and endorsed the funding application in 2023, and then last year we got the funding authorized and we started the design of the project, and we're here this evening for the design public hearing. And now I'm going to turn it over to Megan to discuss the design. Great, so thank you all for having me speak this evening. Um, as you see on the screen here, we have the Fern Street path design. Just to orient yourself as you're looking on the screen, We do have the project twisted to the right. So north is going to be to your right, Fern Street and Park Road. That intersection is on screen left. And the Fairfax Junction Shopping Center is going to be on screen right. This project design is a 10-foot path connector trail. It's 10 feet from the intersection of Park Road and Fern Street. You see that there's two connections that tie to the existing sidewalk that goes along Park Street today. There is a— or a new crosswalk just south on Park Road that exists today. That will be the crossing that exists in this design as well. This path is about 200 feet long. It meanders throughout that green open space that Chloe mentioned. Along the path, it has amenities similar to the Hill Street project that I know that you all are familiar with— amenities such as trash receptacles, lighting, and benches, native trees and plantings along there. We also have a final connection at Fern Street right by that shopping center entrance where we connect to both sidewalks on Fern Street itself, and we will be replacing the entrance at the shopping center to upgrade it to be ADA compliant as part of the connection of this street. Some amenities that are part of the Fern Street project that you can see here are very similar to Hill Street, and you'll see a lot of images that you're familiar with from Hill Street. So those park-like amenities with the trash receptacles, the benches, path-level lighting along there, so very similar to the Hill Street as well with those solar-level path lightings, and then those native trees along the path as well with some plantings at either entrance. You will notice at the entrance of both sides at Park and Fern and also up at the shopping center entrance, we do have lighting to show the entrance of that path. And then along the path itself. So those are the amenities that are planned as part of the project itself and they go along the path for about that 200 feet there making that closed connection. [Speaker:COMMISSIONER TREGONING] Okay. So this is a summary of the public engagement that we have done so far. Going back to the beginning of the project, there was, of course, public engagement as part of the Small Area Plan and as part of the 2-year program. Again, we had that funding open house in the summer of 2023 before we held the public hearing to endorse the funding application. Now, more recently, since we started the design of the project, we updated the information on the Engage page, and this slide was created before the holidays, so there's been a few more visitors. I think there's been about 250 visitors to the Engage page since November, and since we put out exhibits at the park, at the location to show what the exhibits would look like, and we sent out information to the community and asking them for feedback. And we've gotten about 10 comments so far, generally supportive with a variety of suggestions for modifications to some of the amenities. We notified the public in a variety of ways with A-frame signs, we mailed letters to residents immediately adjacent to the project. It was in the City Scene. We did a newspaper ad as required for our public hearing requirements and then put it out through the City email and social media accounts. And then this is the schedule looking forward. So tonight is the public hearing and then the public hearing record will be open through January 23rd. So any comments that we receive tonight as well as the comments that we have already received And then comments that we receive through January 23rd will be in the public hearing record and we will provide written responses to all of those comments. And then following that, we will develop the 100% plans and then send this out for a construction award. So that would be towards the end of this year, we would be looking to wrap up the plans and begin construction. And as far as the project budget, we do have approximately $350,000 in in transportation alternatives, 80% of that is federal money and then 20% of it is the local match from our CNI fund. And that does fund the entire project as it is budgeted right now. So that concludes our presentation. We will be happy to take any questions. Questions? [Speaker:COMMISSIONER TREGONING] All right. Are there any questions for staff on this from the dais? Commissioner Peterson.",
      "snippet": "Motion passed unanimously. We will move on to public hearing. Our first public hearing is on the Fern Street Connector Path Project, and there's no council action on this item tonight. I'm going to recognize Chloe Ritte…"
