      "timestamp_label": "246:19:36",
      "transcript_text": "Councilmember Hardy Chandler. I don't have a question but a comment. As a resident of the neighborhood near this, I've been very impressed with the outreach for input. I get to pass by the signs that invite residents to offer input as I'm walking my dog. I've seen the signage at the site that is really helpful for envisioning what this is going to look like. So I would just say it is hard for someone in that general area to not know that this project is going on. And so I just want to highlight the amount of engagement that has been invited and how it has been invited in different ways. So thank you for that. Other questions? Councilmember McQuillan. Thank you. I too, living in this neighborhood, have to echo those sentiments. Because we do see the outreach, and I appreciate all the effort in keeping our community so educated and informed. Going through the project schedule, at what point will public comments— or have public comments already been included or revised in the design? [Speaker:MS. KELLY] So there were public comments at the funding application stage that were— that we took and incorporated into the design as we started the design. Now we are at the stage where we are collecting another round of public comments and there will be— I expect there will be tweaks to the design based on the comments that we have received so far and any comments that we receive in the next 10 days. [Speaker:COMMISSIONER TREGONING] Okay. So will that occur before the plans become 100% developed? [Speaker:COMMISSIONER TREGONING] Okay. Excellent. Thank you. Appreciate that. [Speaker:COMMISSIONER TREGONING] Other questions? Other questions? [Speaker:COMMISSIONER WRIGHT] Okay. The only comment I am going to make is that, you know, the Hill Street connector in my neighborhood has been a game changer. So, and that was a long time coming, but it has made a difference. And again, the walkability that we are bringing with these small projects just adds to the quality of life in our neighborhoods and connecting them to our small area plans and our activity centers. Can't say enough of how these small projects are major game changers for neighborhoods where two of our council members live and possibly a third of our council member might live. So anyway, um, I will open the public hearing. Miss Shinaberry, has the public hearing been properly advertised? Yes, it has. I had one person sign up to speak prior to the meeting, so I will call that speaker up and then we'll open the floor if there's anybody else that would like to speak on this item. So our first speaker is Douglas Stewart.",
