      "timestamp_label": "451:00:11",
      "transcript_text": "Thank you. Is there anybody else in the room that would like to talk on the Fern Street connector? Okay, um, so I will close the public hearing. There is no council action tonight on this issue. Okay, our next item is a public hearing and council action on an ordinance amending Chapter 102, in parentheses, Utilities, Article 2, in parentheses, Fees and Charges, Section 102-33 pertaining to sanitary sewer connection fees, frontage charges, and wastewater lateral repair and replacement charges, and Article For Wastewater Division 3, Connections to Public Sewers, Section 102-180 pertains to connections to public sewers. I'm going to recognize Annie Feary as a utilities coordinator. Yes, okay, yes, for the staff report. Good evening, Mayor and Council. My name is Anne Feary. I'm the utilities coordinator with the Department of Public Works. Um, this item proposes two changes to the utility ordinance. The first change would be to the Wastewater Lateral Repair and Replacement Program. City Council established the Lateral Repair and Replacement Program in January of 2017, along with a dedicated lateral repair charge to reimburse property owners for eligible sewer lateral repairs and replacements. The program also promotes trenchless rehabilitation methods to extend the life of aging laterals in a cost-effective manner. Since the program's adoption, inflation has signif— significantly increased material and labor costs. With input from the Finance Department, Public Works recommends increasing the maximum reimbursement amounts by 30%, from $2,500 for a partial replacement to $3,250, and then from $5,000 to $6,500 for full replacement. Expenditures, which both align with, um, cumulative inflation. These updates will help ensure the program continues to provide meaningful financial assistance and also support timely repairs. Um, the second amendment for this ordinance, uh, is a revision which clarifies how sewer availability charge credit is applied to existing structures. Um, the city is moving sewer availability fee processing and payment into the electronic ACELA portal, um, and we're coordinating with Code Administration, our department, Public Works, as well as the IT department. Um, currently determining credits for demolished structures requires extensive staff research and is often hindered by incomplete records. Um, the proposed amendments place responsibilities on applicants to identify prior structures and provide supporting documentation of that information. with their plumbing permit applications. That's typically when we receive availability and connection fees is when the trade permits are submitted. Um, we are also planning on noticing the applicants during the building and demolition process of this change that they will need to provide us the existing structure information. If documentation is not submitted, fees will be assessed without credit. Um, these changes will create a clearer and more consistent process for for the plumbing permit and building permit applicants. It improves the accuracy of sewer availability records and also supports the implementation of availability fee payments through the portal as a part of the city's broader goal of consolidating permitting and fee processing into Accela. That concludes the staff report for these two changes, and I'd be happy to answer any questions you might have. Okay, are there any questions of staff? Councilmember Amos.",
