      "start_seconds": 2007020,
      "timestamp_label": "557:30:20",
      "transcript_text": "Councilmember Ramos' comments reminded me that I believe that I have seen at least at at the state level, some legislation that incorporates a provision that allows for rates and whatnot to be adjusted for inflation on a yearly basis kind of automatically. Is that something that we might consider here, or is it just kind of better to, you know, have a conscious decision-making process behind that? [Speaker:CHAIRMAN BRYANT] One of my concerns about this being annual is when we started the program in 2017, We weren't sure how many people were going to apply. People pay a little bit on their bill to build up this account. But Mr. Thosen, who was utilities director back then, we talked about there's a lot of old homes in the city and we wanted to make sure we had enough money in that account in case we got bombarded by lateral replacement requests. So one of the things Satoshi and I and Annie would do is keep track of that account. And when we felt comfortable enough where we could refund people more, that's why we kind of started talking about this because we saw the account. But a few years before, we're like, we don't know how many— I mean, this is open to everybody with a home in the city. So it could— that account could go away real quick if a lot of people apply for that help. So we wanted to make sure we had a pretty good cushion. So doing it every year You know, I'd like to be able to keep track of that account, see how much is in there. Yeah, thanks. I thought it might, you know, be something like that.",
