      "timestamp_label": "584:13:42",
      "transcript_text": "Okay, any other— Councilmember Hall. Sorry, this is still on. Uh, just curious how many people, if we know, have already taken advantage of this. And just a secondary question, you said that, um, the goal is that people submit essentially what they know, but if they don't know and they're a new owner or something like that, they would city would still go and do all the background that it had done previously, correct? Correct. Yeah, so the availability fees apply. So it's kind of— your first question was about the wastewater lateral charge, I think. What was the question? Uh, how many people have taken advantage or had to? Okay, so let me start there because that's, that's kind of the First Amendment. Um, so I looked earlier tonight and it is generally somewhere around 20 to 25 properties a year per fiscal year that have applied for the reimbursement, um, since the implementation. And then your second question, um, in regards to the availability charges, yes, the city will still do their due diligence to see if we have the records on file. Um, this will, uh, likely be more beneficial for larger developments, such as Capstone is a great example. Um, there was a commercial, um, building that had several units and when it came time to figure out or calculate the availability fees that they owed, that building had already been demolished. And so it was really difficult with the records that we have now, because we didn't have a system like Acela, to really determine how much credit they should be owed based on what was existing. So we will still do the research, and we'll still help the applicants the best we can to find that information. I think the— The point of this is to actually streamline it and make sure we have the records as well. Yep. Other questions? Okay. I see none. I will open the public hearing. Ms. Shinabare, has this public hearing been properly advertised? Yes, it has. No one has signed up prior to the meeting. Is there anybody that would like to speak on this agenda item? Well, all right then. Uh, is there a motion? Councilmember Hardy Chandler. I move that the City Council enact the attached ordinance amending Chapter 102, Utilities, Article 2, Fees and Charges, and Article 4, Wastewater Division 3 of the Code of the City of Fairfax, Virginia. Is there a second?",
