      "meeting_id": "jan-13-2026",
      "meeting_date": "2026-01-13",
      "speaker": "Councilmember Anthony Amos",
      "section": "14. Adjournment.",
      "turn_index": 55,
      "start_seconds": 2404420,
      "timestamp_label": "667:53:40",
      "transcript_text": "Thank you. This one is also a little bit of housekeeping. As you all are aware, the public may not be aware, but the, the, there's a statute in Virginia, State and Local Government Conflict of Interest Act, which establishes standards of conduct for certain officers and employees of state and local governments in the Commonwealth. The city has a corollary ordinance which goes beyond the simple requirements in the State and Local Government Act with respect to individuals or positions that are subject to annual financial disclosure requirements. And this ordinance would also update filing deadlines. There have been changes over the past few years, as well as continuing obligations, and also update the provisions related to violations and penalties. Just for clarification, previous to this ordinance, in addition to the enumerated positions, there was also a requirement, in addition to the department heads filing conflict of interest forms, that their deputies would file. In looking at this and comparing with what other jurisdictions do, we could not find any other jurisdiction jurisdictions that require that level of disclosure by— certainly by folks who are not in decision-making positions. So the recommendations are to adopt these changes. It also includes some updated title positions. We now have a Chief Financial Officer. We also include the commissioners of the Economic Development Authority and its executive director, as well as members of the Retirement Plan Administrative Committee. And then again, as noted, all department heads. It updates the requirements. The state requirements now are that these annual disclosures be filed by February 1st. There are also requirements for filing additional forms by certain enumerated individuals. This also reflects the state definition of what constitutes the immediate family of any of the enumerated positions, and that's defined as being any other person who resides in the same household as and is a dependent of persons subject to the scope of the division. The dependency requirement was a change at the state level. Reflecting that. And then we also updated the penalty provisions to correspond to the, uh, to the state enabling authority. With that, happy to answer any questions.",
      "snippet": "Thank you. This one is also a little bit of housekeeping. As you all are aware, the public may not be aware, but the, the, there's a statute in Virginia, State and Local Government Conflict of Interest Act, which establ…"
