      "timestamp_label": "1433:47:17",
      "transcript_text": "Hi, good evening. I'm Gene Iricoli. I live in Mosby Woods. I've been here since 1986, myself and my family, obviously. And I recommend we do not take the money. Everybody's talking about it's a business decision. Everybody's talking about it's the right thing to do. I don't disagree with that. However, nobody's talking about the rape and the carnage of what's going on down there between Draper Park and 123. You're talking about going a beautiful piece of ground with the Akitik Creek runs through with its woodlands and everything else that's associated with the forest. I watched them take those trees out of that area during the creek restoration. All right, 250-year-old oaks, 4-foot diameter trunks, hundreds of them, 400 of them came out of there. The next piece of ground that gets worked on It's going to be 600-plus. I just walked the area twice over the past weekend. You could see it's going to be hard to do. Why would you tear up one of the most beautiful places in, uh, the city of Fairfax for a bike trail? You want to put a bike trail, put a bike trail where it can be accessed. You're going to tear up one of the jewels of Fairfax City for a walking trail and a bike trail. I don't oppose that. I think it's a great thing. Do the right thing in that regard. I've been here for 40 years. I've walked through that place with my 3 kids and my grandchildren. It's beautiful down there. You've got the creek, you got flora and fauna. I don't see how they're going to— when they tear that area up, the connect— try to connect the pieces of the Snyder Trail, it's, it's going to be mixed and matched. I'd be treasure— I'd want to see somebody ride a bike through there. You're going to have to go up up and down and round and round. The track— the ground is treacherous. So what I say, build the trail if you want to, don't appropriate the money now. Get a plan, rewrite the plan. If it's taken 15 years, fine, that means it's hard, it's hard work, you know, you want to get it right. Tearing up that piece of ground is not going to be the right thing to do. The segments I'm talking about, Draper Park to Stafford Drive, Stafford Drive to Fairwoods Parkway, which is right behind CVS. Go over there and look, it looks like somebody raped it with bulldozers and backhoes. And of course, Fairwoods Parkway to Route 123. Uh, let's see, one more piece before I'm done. You have a hard job, I respect that. There are existing walkways in this city, there are existing paths that already exist, they can be connected. Go through creatively, get somebody to do it, and connect them. Doing what? Oh, I'm sorry. All right, so in enclosure— yeah, finish the trail, but finish the right trail. Don't finish the one that takes one of the crown jewels of Fairfax City and tears it apart. It will not be a good decision. Go down to Cambridge Station and see what happened down there. They ruined that whole area. They ruined— thank you very much for your time.",
      "snippet": "Hi, good evening. I'm Gene Iricoli. I live in Mosby Woods. I've been here since 1986, myself and my family, obviously. And I recommend we do not take the money. Everybody's talking about it's a business decision. Everyb…"
