      "turn_index": 90,
      "start_seconds": 5350076,
      "timestamp_label": "1486:07:56",
      "transcript_text": "Our next speaker is Jane Kelsey, then following is Mariana Fournier. Good evening. I'm Jane Kelsey, 4041 Autumn Court, Fairfax City. I've been in the City since 1961 and loved it, and I really I want to tell you that I support the trail. I think they are very important, and not only from my personal standpoint, but I've seen what it does for the other people in the community. We— it's for recreation, that's fine, but it is also for people who want to go up to Main Street. It's— it saves them getting in the car and driving a short distance. And if they've got a trail instead of having to go up and down the streets to get to Main Street, they wouldn't do it. They would take the car. So I think that helps many environmental issues that we have. So I just want to speak to that issue as well as the issue of saving taxpayer money, and I just do not see the math of how you could turn this down and when you've got $21 million and we have to pay $4 million. Just think about the difference between that. When you're just handed the $21 million, why would you give it back? And it seems to me you would just finish what you started a long time ago when it was in the plan, I believe, originally, and do it. It just seems so simple to me, but obviously I'm not having to make the decision for everybody in Fairfax City. But thank you very much. Next speaker is Mariana Fournier, then following would be Jeb Mann. Good evening, I'm Mariana Fournier, 10134 Spring Lake Terrace. The question we should be asking ourselves: if this was such a great project, why wasn't it done years ago? Why did it keep going forward and forward and costing us more and more money? Probably because of the way the council handled it. I'm sorry you weren't upfront with us. You weren't willing to listen to us. We gave you a petition and it was sneered at. If you think we're going to trust the city council with spending more money You gotta be kidding me. I saw the picture today of what you've already done. This isn't— this is environmental rape. I'm sorry, but if this was a good program, then you should have worked it out some way and have gotten it taken care of years ago. I believe it was because you dug your heels in and there was only one way to do it and you weren't willing to compromise. You weren't willing to listen to us. And you— and the prior councils just frankly blew it. Why should we trust you anymore? And as far as spending money, this is a money pit. It's going to cost more and more and more because you haven't really done this appropriately. There are going to be additional costs that you are not even thinking about. And we're saying not a penny more. And if anyone wants to discuss the issue with me, you know where I live, and I'll even make the coffee. But I wish you had this prior councils had been willing to sit down and talk to their citizens instead of assuming that they had the right answer. I mean you no disrespect. Consider this a fraternal correction. Thank you very much. Next speaker is Jeff Mann, then following would be Henry Mann.",
      "snippet": "Our next speaker is Jane Kelsey, then following is Mariana Fournier. Good evening. I'm Jane Kelsey, 4041 Autumn Court, Fairfax City. I've been in the City since 1961 and loved it, and I really I want to tell you that I…"
