      "start_seconds": 5804200,
      "timestamp_label": "1612:16:40",
      "transcript_text": "My name is Henry Mann. I live at 9744 Cardinal Road, and that was my dad that just spoke, and I wanted to correct correct him, there are actually two herons that we have seen together. They're— I mean, I can confidently say I've lived in the same house all my life. I can confidently say that I know the woods that the George Schneider Trail is going to go through more than basically anybody in this room. I know when I think of the George Schneider Trail and like the area that it's going to go through, I think not necessarily of the woods as much as the people that go through it. I think that there's a lot of waste that I've had to pick up in the last week. I walk to school. Going home, I've picked up at least 10 pounds of trash in the last 3 days. Wait, it's a Tuesday. 2 days, sorry. That's like, that's where my mind's at right now, but if more people come in there, that's going to be more more of an issue. We're going to have to worry about cleaning up trash. We're gonna have to worry about— I mean, I've heard about policeman numbers too, right? We have to add more policemen to the staff, and the police is understaffed as it is. I might be wrong on that. Anyway, I wanted to clarify some more things that people have said though. The idea that the George Snyder Trail really crosses through the city and crosses and passes the city's businesses. I mean, no, it— there's a Wawa kind of near where the Wilcoxon Trail lets out, and that's it. I mean, if you go through those woods, there's not much else until— I mean, unless you want to check into the Best Western. That's basically it. It's Wawa to Best Western, and there's woods, and there's nothing else. If we really want to advertise Fairfax City as it is to the greater people, which we are very considerate of, to the greater county, we should pass it through the real part of Fairfax City where the businesses are, where we want to showcase what we have.",
