      "turn_index": 97,
      "start_seconds": 6127434,
      "timestamp_label": "1702:03:54",
      "transcript_text": "Thank you. Good evening, Mayor and Council. My name is Chris French. I live at 3172 Stratford Court, and I'm the president of Northern Virginia Families for Safe Streets, an all-volunteer organization focused on advocating for street safety, specifically pedestrian safety, throughout the region. We have more than 2,000 members and have chapters in Alexandria, Arlington, and Fairfax. I do communicate regularly with Chloe Ritter regarding the city's transportation initiatives, and we were happy to be offered a seat at the table in the Move Fairfax City Advisory Committee. I've come today to speak in strong support of the George Snyder Trail. I'll start by sharing that our Fairfax chapter is a member of Fairfax Healthy Communities, a network of 22 nonprofits working in the intersecting areas of active transportation, Smart Growth, Environment, Housing, and Food Security. Network partners envision a region where people can live, work, and play in connected communities that are healthy, sustainable, and inclusive. We believe safe and comfortable routes to walk, bike, use transit, and get to the places we need to and want to go without relying on driving is integral to making our communities more sustainable and healthier. And contributes to a local— a vibrant local economy. This project works to achieve that vision. I certainly acknowledge the trail's construction will not be without impact. However, I believe there are considerable benefits that will be realized. The trail will provide a much-needed, currently missing connection between the 66 Parallel Trail and the CCT and Wilcoxon Trails, in addition to providing connectivity to this larger regional trail network that The trail will provide benefits to local residents by expanding active transportation options for all ages and all abilities to get to school, work, Metro and other transit, restaurants and retail, and many other destinations comfortably, safely, and with low levels of stress. Active transportation projects such as these reduce car dependency and VMT, or vehicle miles traveled, thereby aligning with regional climate goals due to the accompanying reductions in greenhouse gas emissions, but they also help in other ways, such as reducing acute tailpipe pollutants, mitigating traffic congestion and suburban sprawl, while encouraging physical activity, social connection, and overall improvements to public health. Further, greater access to the outdoors for all ages and abilities can help grow appreciation for and stewardship for our natural resources. To close, I'll say that I often find myself at hearings meetings such as this, speaking in support of policies and actions which put people's needs at the center of decision-making to ensure safe, livable, accessible, sustainable, and green communities. Thank you for allowing me the time to do that— just that again tonight.",
