      "timestamp_label": "1750:35:48",
      "transcript_text": "I speak tonight representing the Friends of Accotink Creek regarding the George Snyder Trail. Down, down, down into the darkness of the grave. Gently they go, the beautiful, the tender, the kind. The fish, the toad, the fern, the sycamore, the maple. Down they go for our convenience, for our whims, for our sins. Down they go that we adults may ride our toys upon their two dooms. The year is 2026. It is not 1726 when colonists carved a new society toward the horizon. It is not 1826 when land without end was needed to feed and clothe our growing multitudes. It is not 1926 when the newly ascended automobile could spread its tracks over an unpaved continent. No, the year is 2026 when we find ourselves become the guardians of our last remnants of woods and wetlands. when the insatiable demands of humans have backed the natural world to the brink. When it is time to curb our desires in favor of protecting what remains of nature. We have learned now that the cost of the George Schneider Trail has become too high in dollars we can count. We should have learned before the start that the cost was already too high in those things whose value is beyond counting. Please do not continue with the George Schneider Trail or similar projects to pave through our last woods and wetlands. Thank you.",
