      "timestamp_label": "1826:22:07",
      "transcript_text": "Good evening, Douglas Cox, Fairview Drive. You guys have my address. Anyways, uh, most of you have already made up your minds. I'm not for it. I've actually— unlike 99% of the city ridden all the way around to get to the 66 Trail from Fairview. Long way. Uh, it's accessible, it's easy, it's not a big deal, it's entirely safe. So not a fan of this. Plus, let's be honest, you don't have metrics to say how many people use the I-66 Trail at 123. It's built, it's there. How many people cross? How many use it? Unique users, individual users? You don't know. No one ever took metrics. Never figured out how much sediment goes into the stream if you build this thing. You know, you spend all that money on the TMDL and now you're gonna blow it by wiping away and putting this trail. So anyways, let's get into some truth because it seems like a lot of people are confused here. This trail does not come anywhere near the cross-county trail to the west. Cross County Trail goes up Blake Lane, Germantown, ends up going behind Oakmont. So people going, you go through the city and you meet the cross country— not even close. If Oakmont and the Moose Lodge are next to each other, that's fantasy world. Let's stop with that nonsense. And on the other side, let's be truthful, city scene, uh, what do we say here? ADA accessible trail complete. An important missing link between I-66 trail through the city to connect with the Jerry Connelly Cross Country Trail. It does not. George Snyder Trail does not connect to the cross country trail. Will Coxon Trail does. So if you come down the Snyder Trail to the east, go down 50 a little ways, the unsafe highway that we can't get on, catch Will Coxon, then you hit the CCT. But saying they connect is like saying Washington State connects to Alaska. All right? They don't. So let's quit with the nonsense, quit with the lies. Let's all be honest about what this does, where it goes, and also how did we get here. This thing almost got killed in the May-June timeframe. And the city was supposed to have until December. To talk amongst ourselves. And then all of a sudden VDOT threw out, nope, you— in May, you have to decide by June. So talks were made, votes were done. June, you guys sent— June 10th, you sent a thing out to VDOT and said, yep, we're going forward. The bill came in, it was hired. Now here we are talking about it. And I got to say, this is a bad look. Bill Cutler, who wrote the letter from VDOT that said make your decision by June, 2 days after you made the decision, here's the mayor with Bill Cutler, thumbs up. It's a bad look. If there was collusion, shame on you.",
      "snippet": "Good evening, Douglas Cox, Fairview Drive. You guys have my address. Anyways, uh, most of you have already made up your minds. I'm not for it. I've actually— unlike 99% of the city ridden all the way around to get to th…"
