      "transcript_text": "Our next speaker is Avril Garland, and following is Ellen Penn. Hi, I live in the town of Vienna. I'm a member of Friends of Acton Creek, and I— it's very confusing. You have a terrible job ahead of you. I thank very much the 3 council members who have had the foresight and courage to oppose this wrong-headed recreational development, which is undesired by many residents. Residents. Honestly, I can't tell. Somebody said the opposing side, they have broad— said they have broad support. I'm against it. I see people here against it. But how many people are against the trail? How many people want the trail? Do we even know this? I know Arlington County did a survey on deer. Do we want to cull the deer? Sharpshooting, archery, private yards, parks. I mean, I don't think we know what residents I suggest you go and find out, go door to door. The other thing we're talking— the other issue that you talked about was the gain. Yes, you do have a certain amount of gain. I'm on a bicycle and I don't particularly like using Route 50 or Route 66. I mean a path through the— a paved path through the woods. Yeah, I'd like that. But look at the cost. I don't want that to come with the price tag. Price. These barred owls live in the woods, the herons, the finches, the thrushes, the deer, the salamanders, the box turtles. These woods are— to feed them, to feed 500 trees to the chipper, that's a terribly high cost. Or to replace the 500, 600 trees by little sticks and tubes that it's going to take 100 years to grow, as somebody pointed out. Yeah, the trail would be nice, but the cost is really so terrible. You'd be losing— think of what you would be losing. And I think what you're losing would be greatly more than what you're gaining. So I'd ask you to please oppose the trail or find some other ways of making the roads safer. Thank you. Our next Speaker:ELLEN PENNS, 3211 ADAMS COURT. I just realized I have been a resident of Cambridge Station for 58 years now. I am going to read a letter that was written to you today to was given to me. It says, dear council members, I have asked Ellen Pence to read this letter on behalf of me, Rebecca Caldwell, president of Mosby Woods Condominium Association. I speak on behalf of the 168 families who live in our community. We were extremely disappointed to learn in the last 2 years that our entire forest forest would be removed with a creek restoration project and a bike roadway. A dozen years ago, we lost one-third of our neighborhood forest but gained a field and playground in Stafford Park. Right now, we cannot stand to have any more large projects. We watched our mature forest be taken away by stream restoration. Initially, we were very excited about the prospect of lowering the floodplain. However, the new creek has already flooded our homes. If the other half of our forest is removed, the runoff problem will be worse. There are also ponds of standing water, which will be horrible in about 2 months, as soon as the weather is warm enough for mosquitoes. We are told that they were a stake and are going to have drainage ditches done, but there is still standing water. Who is going to maintain this properly? Our forest is already half gone. Please don't take the other half. The children of our neighborhood used to explore and look for wildlife in and around the creek and play in the woods. We liked the fresh air filtered by the mature forest. We had a barrier between us and Stafford Park and Fairfax Boulevard with all of the trees. We are now having problems with rodents and have seen foxes, raptors, raccoons, and deer come— coming in close to the buildings since there is nowhere else for them to live. The surrounding neighborhoods are fine with bike lanes going on Cardinal Road. Please use this route instead taking down the rest of our mature forest. The wetlands to the west of us are protected so that that part of the project cannot go forward. Please leave things the way they are. My final thoughts for you are these: our community does not want to be disturbed with any more construction, and we want to keep what small part of our mature forest remains. Thank you. Rebecca Caldwell. President Mosby Woods Council of Co-Owners. Next speaker, Sophie McNeil. Then following is Toby Sorensen. Hello, my name is Sophie McNeil. I live at 3417 Newberry Road, and for my whole life I've lived in Country Club Hills and grew up playing in the forest. You know, I'm speaking for myself, family, friends, neighbors who cannot be here tonight but are also opposed to the trail. Not only are there numerous environmental issues with funding this trail, but now it's come to light that this trail is incredibly over budget, and for such a short length of trail. As mentioned many times, a trail system already exists, and I'd like to ask again, how well are those maintained? How can we trust that the new trail will be taken care of? Um, I could recite many environmental issues that this trail poses, but you've heard them all before. And I just graduated with a bachelor's, my degree in environmental science. I've worked on wetland restorations, forest surveys, all that type of stuff. And the trail would just destroy vital ecosystems, and they just won't bounce back by planting saplings. Um, passing these plans, supporting the budget addition. Though that's not the right decision, it is the selfish one. Can we think about something other than our own personal benefit, these anthropocentric views, for once? I urge you guys to please stop these destructive plans. And not to mention, I've heard we may not even have to repay it. Thank you very much. Our next speaker is Toby Sorensen, and following is Jennifer Rose.",
