      "transcript_text": "Well, I can't because they need to see that. Okay. Really tried to get this in for a video conference taped, uh, uh, speech, but didn't— missed— I missed a deadline, so Thank you. Good evening. I'm Tom Blackburn of the Northern Virginia Bird Alliance. I want to give you a visual sense of the extent of the destruction at just a few of the points on the George Snyder Trail using photos taken at the locations shown on Stantec's design plans for the City's website. Slide 1 is a view from the start of the trail at Route 123. The first excavation starts just 150 feet away. Two-thirds of this trail is going to be significantly above or below the existing grade. Slide 2. At 280 feet from the start, the trail will be 8 feet below grade. On the right side, the slope to connect with the surrounding terrain will be 22 feet wide And on the left side, there will be a retaining wall 10 feet high plus footers 3 feet below grade. Slide 3 gives you an idea of how far below grade the excavation will be at that point. And the excavation is 275 feet long. Slide 4. The trail switches from above ground to below ground at 425 feet from the start. Here at 500 feet on the slide, the trail will be built on 4 feet of fill dirt with slopes 32 feet wide to grade down to the existing grade. The trail will be on fill for 175 feet. Slide 5. A new section of trail begins on fill dirt 775 feet from the start. At 900 feet here, the fill dirt will be 3 feet high with slopes to the surrounding terrain 23 feet wide. This section of fill is 255 feet long, and then the trail switches back to below ground again. Slide 6. At 2,000— 2,075 feet from the start, the trail will be built on 8 feet of fill dirt to reach the first of 4 14-foot-wide bridges. The slope to the surrounding terrain will be 40 feet wide. Slide 7 shows you just how far above grade the trail will be at the point where it meets the bridge. Slide 8. West of Fairwoods Parkway, the trail will be built on the side of a steep slope requiring retaining walls. 675 feet west of Fairwoods, the retaining wall will be 14 feet high plus footers 5.5 feet below grade. The wall will be 312 feet long. Slide 9. East of Fairwoods, there is significant cross slope requiring a retaining wall 3 to 6 feet high and 175 feet long. To make the trail level from side to side. Slide 10, 75 feet east of Fair— Stafford Drive, the trail will be up to 6 feet below grade, requiring excavated slopes 36 feet wide to meet the surrounding terrain. That excavation will be 150 feet long. Slide 11 gives you an idea of how far below grade the trail will be at that point. If you vote to fund this trail, your legacy will be the destruction of much of Fairfax City's urban forest. Thank you.",
