      "timestamp_label": "2322:51:31",
      "transcript_text": "Mr. Blackburn was the last speaker who signed up prior to the meeting. I'm going to go ahead and do the two video testimonies that we received. Give me one second. All right, our first video is from Marissa Perrone. Hi, my name is Marissa Perrone. I live at 9892 Cardinal Road. I'm speaking tonight in support of the George Schneider Trail. I have two small kids. That's why I can't be with you tonight. But they are big fans of walking and biking everywhere. They think it's so much more fun than riding in a car, and I do too. I think good trails build good neighbors. And I think that if we were more connected to places that are really within walking distance, we'd see a lot more people visiting city businesses and, you know, driving local traffic to those businesses. You look at places like Arlington, and that's just what we're lacking here in Fairfax is is that connectivity and feeling that togetherness that trails bring. I wanna share a story of something that happened recently. I was visiting Compass Coffee with my daughter. She was riding along in a bike trailer with me. So very obviously a mom and her 7-year-old daughter behind her. And we visited Compass Coffee on the way back. We pushed the button to get the pedestrian sign to cross the road at Eaton Place, and, um, someone waited for us, uh, someone who is taking a right turn waited for us to, um, cross the street, waited very patiently. Well, a line of 5 cars got behind this person and they were laying on their horns, just absolutely raging at the fact that someone waited, uh, to cross. Um, and it's because we're not used to seeing pedestrians in this area. Um, it, it, and bikers, it feels like we don't even exist. Um, everyone's just so focused on getting to where they need to be in a car-centric society that they're not really thinking about people on bikes. So I was very grateful that somebody was willing to wait for me, but a little shocked that so many people just thought it was ridiculous that someone would wait for me even though it's the law. I think building more, you know, bike-centric spaces would create more of a sense of safety for all of us. And, you know, for our kids too. I think that I would love to see a world where our kids are able to like walk to a coffee shop to hang out with their friends. That would promote a sense of independence that I think that our generations are really lacking. So I think I think that supporting this trail is supporting the future of Fairfax, and let's think about our kids when we vote. Thanks. Our next video is from Sherry Steely. Good evening. I'm Sherry Steely, and I'm here tonight to talk about the George Snyder Trail project. The project intends to transform this small footpath through the woods adjacent to Ranger Road Park into a 14 to 16-foot wide paved road, necessitating the removal of more than 500 mature trees. The project has several important fiscal governance and environmental problems. First, the current price tag stands at $24 $4 million and rising. Still, there has been, in my opinion, an under-budgeting of maintenance costs and security challenges. To be ADA compliant, the trail will need regular clearing, and staffing for such endeavors has not yet been addressed. Similarly, security and emergency services have not been discussed in conjunction with this project. In terms of other projects, we have just invested heavily in the stream restoration, and that project entailed creation of anti-erosion measures. The George Snyder Trail will circle very close to the Akatin Creek. And this video shows flooding even without the removal of 500 mature trees that the George Snyder Trail would entail. Next, in terms of governance, there is a NEPA document filed which stated that there is no substantial controversy to the project. On the horizon. However, there is significant public opposition on record dating back to 2020, and more recently a petition with more than 3,000 signatures. There is a significant environmental impact that is well recorded with input from very specialized groups who have shared their expertise with the city. Even the city's own master plan, with its chapter on environment and sustainability, undermines the precepts of the project. Thank you to all those council members who continue to exercise fiscal restraint and environmental stewardship. And I urge you all to factor in these considerations in making your decision. Thank you. That was our last video testimony at this time. If there's anybody else in the room that would like to speak to this item, if I can ask you please line up by the window side and come up one at a time stating your name and street address and comment. Hi, I want to respect everybody's time and the passion of all that have been speaking tonight. Um, my name is Erin Mazzi, I live at 106 or 10165 Fairwoods Drive in the Mosby Woods Condominiums. So I, I rent, but I talk to my neighbors who are owners, and one of them has also asked me to quote her concerns of calling this an abomination of a plan and cost, and is highly concerned about what tearing down so much of this green space protection from noise, all the construction, is going to do to her own property. Values as well. I can't really speak outside as much of the context because this green space in this area was a large part of why I moved here. These trails and the opportunities for transit have been such an important part of why I've remained in Fairfax for the 3 years that I have since I moved to this community. And I love that— me and my husband both love that we don't drive very much already. We could walk to the CVS, we could walk and get sushi. And this is an area that already has significant access, um, and good access along the roads to reach, um, businesses and to go to these communities. And I see my neighbors taking it all the time. I hear a lot of wonderful things about building community, about the future, and I can tell you that my neighbors are already out there on these streets. They're already walking these trails. They're already using and experiencing and enjoying the nature, and this is not the correct way to move forward and to connect more, more people. It just isn't. It's— it feels more like a way to put essentially a highway through our parks and playgrounds that we already have, and including like, I I'm just baffled to see that this trail, especially with high speed, it goes next to at least 3 playgrounds along the way or straight through them as they go through. I don't— and just seeing the grade of the terrain, seeing like walking on it, like it's baffling that this is the spot to build such an extensive construction. I'm— I, again, I love these trails. I love everything that I've experienced about being in Fairfax. Fairfax, especially when it comes to transit, especially when it comes to the investment, things like Tree City. And that means a lot to me. And so far, like, we've had a wonderful experience. I'll tell you, though, that like looking out my window at the stream restoration is already pretty much almost enough to make us leave and move somewhere else. And the burden has already fallen so significantly. And it also baffles me me to hear people talk about affordable housing, to talk about business and about improvement, when there is already one of the more affordable communities here that I live in that is bearing the brunt of the environmental impacts. It is already— and it does make me doubt the sincerity of the people who say this. So thank you for all of your time. I respect it's a difficult decision, and the passion of supporters and opponents as well.",
      "snippet": "Mr. Blackburn was the last speaker who signed up prior to the meeting. I'm going to go ahead and do the two video testimonies that we received. Give me one second. All right, our first video is from Marissa Perrone. Hi,…"
