      "transcript_text": "Good evening, Mayor and Council. I'm Roger Custer, 10131 Cardinal Road, and we have the privilege of backing up to the forest that is proposed to be cut down for this project. And one of the animals who lives in that forest, uh, my kids have dubbed Freddy the Fox, and we love it when he comes into our backyard and explores through Mosby Woods. But I fear that this project will be cutting down his home along with many other animals and species that we enjoy in our wonderful city. Uh, and you've heard about all the other environmental impacts. I don't need to repeat that. I'd like to urge you to consider not appropriating the money and canceling the project. And I have a unique proposal for what we can do, uh, as a city to achieve our common goals here, uh, to be a tree city, to have an urban forest, and to be proud of our wilderness and our trees, which is I think we should work together to obtain federal funds for open space. Uh, we have the Parks Foundation, which potentially could raise money I'm a professional nonprofit fundraiser, and I would personally be happy to help put together a coalition to save this forest and really make maybe even an example for other cities that are having this discussion about development or not development. And really, I think we could work together to do that, to have a positive solution here that really meets the goals of everyone who's been speaking tonight for our city. So I hope we can do that. I hope we can save Freddie the Fox and move forward with Fairfax together. Thank you very much.",
