      "start_seconds": 12362870,
      "timestamp_label": "3434:07:50",
      "transcript_text": "Lassner. Oops. I will be brief. It is hard to really add too much to what everybody else has said. I think it is very important to thank everybody who attended, not just who came this evening, but obviously all the people who are watching and those of you who submitted video testimony. It is really great. All of that information is extremely helpful and it has been. All along the way. So I'll tell you that one of the difficulties that I had with the setup for this public hearing this evening is that it was based on the premise that we had only 4 options, and that's clearly not the case. We have a great many other options. We began a process last year to begin looking at those, very much with the agreement and encouragement of VDOT and the community. And people were genuinely excited about the opportunity to look at different approaches here that could reconcile the conflicts that so clearly exist with this project in comparison with the desires that people have to have the kind of trail you have heard talked about this evening, something very simple. And at the same time, be able to make improvements on the way we can use bikes on our streets in the city. Unfortunately, that process was terminated very quickly. To this very day, we don't know why. We did our best at the council to try to understand why it didn't happen. It's past history. We ended up with where we are today, and I think what I've heard this evening is that that has been seen as a very difficult proposition for most people in the city, and that has been the case for a very long time. I do think, um, it's time to move on, and I think that we have, um, really a lot of good reasons not only to move on here today but to look forward to other opportunities and options. I, I will just close by saying that it's a bit fitting that we will be making a decision this evening through an appropriations vote. And just a reminder that an appropriations vote ended the Vietnam War. And I think it may be time to end this war. We've been at this a long time. It's time to move on. One of my brothers was number one in the last draft of the Vietnam War. He did not go to Southeast Asia because of the Hatfield-McGovern Amendment. On an appropriation. He was greatly relieved that he didn't have to go to war, but it did not stop his patriotism and it did not stop his service to his country. He enlisted in the United States Marine Corps and he served many years. We have a very dear friend in the same situation, the exact same time, who went on to become a Navy fighter pilot, active duty, er, active duty on carriers. He served his country. He was a patriot. Neither of them wanted to go to that war. Neither of them believed in it, but they believed in their country, just as we all here believe in our community. They served because they fought— they thought there was a better way. They thought there was a better venue for them to serve. And I think there's a better venue for us all here in the community to approach our interest in trails and our stewardship. This particular course of action that we have been now looking at for a great many years does not appear to be that course. There are other courses out there. And we can recommit ourselves to looking at new opportunities by moving on. I will not be appropriating— excuse me, I will not be supporting the appropriation for those reasons and I think one other that was alluded to by a number of English speakers, but I don't think it's a great idea to build a project simply because you will be penalized if you don't. And I don't think VDOT wants that. I don't think we want that. I don't think that's the right way to proceed. There is, in fact, a better way for us all to move forward. Thank you.",
