      "timestamp_label": "3721:53:35",
      "transcript_text": "That concludes that. Okay, we can go on to second general public comment. Is there anybody— is there anybody in the room that wants to talk about anything that was not on the agenda for public hearings? Yeah, yeah, you come up. Uh, good evening. Good evening. My name is Beth Iannetta. I live at 10916 Berry Street in the Westmoor community, and I'm here to talk about the Westmoor community. Recently, as you know, the carts have been distributed and delivered, and the Westmoor school site was used as the staging area for that project. I want to first say a big thank you to the project manager, Melissa McDonald, who spoke to me and was kind of a point of contact as Things were happening and kind of going wrong. Overall, she is great. She handled some of the projects— some of the problems that popped up. I will say that a Fairfax Water contractor knocked our power out on Thursday because they are using the Westmore School site as a construction laydown area. On Friday, the 18-wheelers that were coming through on Chestnut pull down power on two different residents. Hardy Chandler, you might— we're neighbors with them, so you might have seen it. And so my point is, is that I, I am going to be speaking with park staff and do through other means, but a conversation on how West— that Westmoor quote-unquote park is used needs to happen sooner than later. We are basically using it as a city extra site for storage, construction laydown areas, delivery carts, and things of that nature, and it's really not appropriate for the things— we use it for parking for the leaf trucks when the city site floods. We're using it for things that are not parks, and I know it's formally not a park, but I think we need to have a strong conversation about how we're going to be using that and make sure its future is solidified as a feature and an asset to our community. And not someplace we can just go dump some things when the city needs a place to put it. It's deep in our neighborhood. It's not really an appropriate place to be used for that. And so I really welcome your help in getting those conversations moving forward with the appropriate staff. But a big shout out to Melissa McDonald, who did an excellent job in troubleshooting these, these problems as they happened. And so I just want to make— go on the record and make sure she gets some recognition for that and the hard work that she's doing. So thank you very much. Appreciate your night and talk to you later. Can I say something? I would like to say that many times we don't take the moment to appreciate what is happening in the city. There's a lot good is happening in the city and we absolutely need to reflect. I mean, I wrote a note to my principal that I need to pause and appreciate what you are doing in writing. And I would like to do that for the City Public Works. And it goes hand in hand with the entire Department of Public Works. The way our Fairfax City is maintained, you cross the city limits and you can see the curbs where vegetation is growing. You can tell where the Fairfax City begins and ends. So a big applause to the Public Works staff who maintains the common ground. It's a lot of work to do that. And I truly, like, feel proud of being a Fairfax City resident. Being part of the ESC and seeing the work of Stephanie and Melissa and Anna, I'm so proud that I'm part of that committee. Such big work is being done there by the members. And this whole cart has been a bit controversial, but once it comes, it is going to be a great saying. And I know you people have seen my picture with the card, so hey, yeah, you know, I was happy that I was part of that program. And thank you for everything you guys do. It's very tough. Whether you run for the election again or you don't, your effort, each one of you, has been appreciated, because the amount of time you spend until 12:00 and 1:00 that you sit here while we lay in beds is hard. It's not easy. And then to read these piles of files that you guys go through, it's hard. So please do understand that when we come with a passion, each one of us have our passions, we shouldn't be divided. This should bring us together, that we are all humans, we have our passions, and we need to just be together as one human being. Thank you. Anybody else in the room that would like to speak? We can move on to future meeting topics.",
