      "start_seconds": 13995333,
      "timestamp_label": "3887:35:33",
      "transcript_text": "I think the manager's basically covered the talking points that I was going to reiterate of Yes, uh, February 24th, the manager will present his budget. For about 5 to 6 weeks thereafter of meetings, we will go have a work session, every single work session, along with some public hearings that are required. The work sessions, very similar to last year, will have specific topics that we can cover. Council can definitely add or subtract to that. And then, as the manager stated, this year, similar to previous years, We will be engaging with Council via one-on-ones or one-on-twos prior to the 24th to sort of get some feedback, and then if need be, try to adjust accordingly depending on what the manager feels is appropriate. That answer your question, Councilmember? I, I think so. So my quick translation is we're going to get a head start. Yes, sir. Thank you. So moving on to very quickly the next two meetings. On the 3rd, for the work session, joint meeting of the Planning Commission and City Council regarding the draft FY 2027-2031 CIP. So that speaks to another part of our process for budget, joint discussion with Environmental Sustainability Committee and programs that are associated with that program. Solid Waste Management Plan update and then a discussion with city departments on assigned staffing tasks related to public safety and the ordinances and articles and chapters are listed there for the third. And I will just quickly jump to the tenth, update and discussion on the citywide Level of Service study which will assess impacts and cost implications of new development on city services. Resources and Infrastructure, Introduction of Draft Small Area Plan Zoning Ordinance Amendments, Discussion on the Development of the Green Building Policy, and Discussion and Update on the Willard Sherwood Community Center. That's the next two meetings. I would be happy to answer any questions associated with those meetings. Councilmember Pedersen. The third is a packed agenda in terms of the information load. Budget, and I would say quality. These are things we all have been looking forward to. I'm guessing there's going to be a lot of reading in advance, probably. I know we'll be seeing presentations, but if there is reading that we're expected to do or would be helpful, given the volume of that, I would just ask that we have it as early as possible so that we can be prepped up. It's a lot of information, and we'll— be in better shape, I think, to ask smart questions if we do that. Thank you. And then, um, on February 10, Item 2, the introduction of the Small Area Plan zoning amendments, um, just as soon as possible, whether it's this evening or some other time soon, it would be helpful to understand the gist of what is being proposed and why. In terms of amendments and to get started early on the thought process around that. I know the small area planning process involves a lot of history and a lot of complexity, so I would love to get a little bit of clarity on what exactly we are trying to accomplish and what we will be looking at as part of that.",
