      "start_seconds": 14342669,
      "timestamp_label": "3984:04:29",
      "transcript_text": "I think the first thing I'd like to do is thank Melanie Zipp for all the help that you have given us over the past year as we have gone through the process of bringing in a new permanent city manager. Dan, it's really, really good to have you, but Melanie, it's really, really good to have had you and everything you did to help us over that past year, which I found really helpful and done with a fair degree of grace, which was doubly helpful under the circumstances. So thanks, thanks again for all that. Um, just a kind of a regional note. So we, we serve, all of us, on various regional boards and commissions, and Mayor Reed and I both serve on transportation-related boards and commissions. I attended a couple of them this last few weeks. The Transportation Planning Board, I stepped in for the Mayor on the Northern Virginia— Transportation Commission. NVTC. I know the acronym, but the words escape me. I think that there— just to pass on maybe two takeaways from those conversations that took place. One is we are in a period of leadership change. Leadership transition, and we're now looking at new people stepping into place at the state level, but there's a lot of that filtering into various positions, and it's particularly filtering into everything in the transportation network. So there are going to be a lot of new faces and a lot of new things discussed in different ways as a part of that. At the same time, the other big theme that came out on the environmental side of things. It is, I think, more necessary than ever for the local jurisdictions themselves, like the City of Fairfax, but other cities and counties and towns, to take direct action on the environment as it relates to transportation. Leadership as opposed to expecting the regional bodies to take that action. I think the environment we are operating in right now is pushing that leadership down to a lower level here. So I particularly appreciate everything we are talking about on the environmental front, you know, in the upcoming meetings we have. But really, it— the consideration of environment is about as frontline as you can get right now. Going to stay frontline for a while, although we are certainly looking forward to new state leadership. David Bulova will be secretary, and that is certainly an enormous benefit to us here. But I just wanted to note that this is an area of sort of active recognition in these regional bodies right now, that we're living in a different world in terms of the need for us to step up to the plate played on the environmental side. Thank you.",
